05967nam a22009975i 9781487530143DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192019onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875301437 a10.3138/97814875301432doi  a(DE-B1597)527534  a(OCoLC)1091899563  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aDC128 7aHIS0100002bisacsh04a944/.0332231 aStone, Harriet, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCrowning Glories :bNetherlandish Realism and the French Imagination during the Reign of Louis XIV /cHarriet Stone. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (312 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tImages -- tAcknowledgments -- tCROWNING GLORIES -- tIntroduction: Hiding in Plain Sight -- tPart I: Divergent Patterns -- t1. Two Models in Context: Northern Realist Art in France -- t2. France at the Intersection: Configuring the French Response to Northern Realism -- tPart II: Transformations -- t3. Fractured Spaces: Staging the King’s Portrait -- t4. In Death as in Life -- tPart III: Patterns of Change -- t5. The Great Reveal -- t6. Legacies -- tCoda: Trompe L’oeil Illusions and the Thoughts They Inspire -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCrowning Glories integrates Louis XIV’s propaganda campaigns, the transmission of Northern art into France, and the rise of empiricism in the eighteenth century – three historical touchstones – to examine what it would have meant for France’s elite to experience the arts in France simultaneously with Netherlandish realist painting. In an expansive study of cultural life under the Sun King, Harriet Stone considers the monarchy’s elaborate palace decors, the court’s official records, and the classical theatre alongside Northern images of daily life in private homes, urban markets, and country fields. Stone argues that Netherlandish art assumes an unobtrusive yet, for the history of ideas, surprisingly dramatic role within the flourishing of the arts, both visual and textual, in France during Louis XIV’s reign. Netherlandish realist art represented thinking about knowledge that challenged the monarchy’s hold on the French imagination, and its efforts to impose the king’s portrait as an ideal and proof of his authority. As objects appreciated for their aesthetic and market value, Northern realist paintings assumed an uncontroversial place in French royal and elite collections. Flemish and Dutch still lifes, genre paintings, and cityscapes, however, were not merely accoutrements of power, acquisitions made by those with influence and money. Crowning Glories reveals how the empirical orientation of Netherlandish realism exposed French court society to a radically different mode of thought, one that would gain full expression in the Encyclopédie of Diderot and d’Alembert.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aArt and societyzFrancexHistoryy17th century. 0aArts, Frenchy17th century. 0aPainting, Dutchy17th centuryxInfluence. 0aPainting, Flemishy17th centuryxInfluence. 0aRealism in artxHistoryy17th century. 4aDISCOUNT-B. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh  aDutch Golden Age.  aFrench.  aLouis XIV.  aNetherlandish realism.  aNorthern realism.  aSun King.  acentury.  aclassical theatre.  acourt culture.  acultural production.  acultures.  aearly modern period.  aeighteenth.  aepistemology.  ahistory of ideas.  aknowledge.  arise of empiricism.  asystems.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE CO